I think one idealistic goal of biology and medicine should be improving reading speed in a meaningful way. The topic is poisoned by low brow "speedreading" concepts, sub-vocalizations, flow state inanities, etc., but a good description would be "regular" reading taking less time.

I think it was Roger Scruton (?) who claimed he was able to read 2000 pages per day, which seems silly, T. Roosevelt also said he could read 1-2 books per busy day. I think with a high enough metabolism it would be possible to comfortably read 200 pages in an hour w/o rushing it.

My bad, it was Harold Bloom claiming 500-700 pages per *hour*, which I also believe is probably e-statting similar to people rounding up their deadlift PR numbers, but I also think it's probably possible to achieve like ~200/hour at a comfortable and even contemplatory speed.
